The response directly addresses the user's plateau issue by requesting the loss curve shape and proposing concrete diagnostics before any changes. It emphasizes the overfit-tiny test, gradient norm tracking, and an LR-range test, and explicitly rejects the "bigger model" reflex. The ordered action list reinforces that diagnostics come first.

```json
{
  "case_id": "case-01",
  "specialist": "ml-training-takin",
  "rubric_scores": [
    {
      "criterion": "asks_for_loss_curve_shape_or_grad_norm",
      "evidence": "\"The Takin needs the curve.\" ... \"1. **Curve shape.** Plot loss every 10 steps for the first 500 steps and every 100 steps thereafter.\" ... \"3. **Gradient norm per layer.** Healthy is grad-norm / param-norm in `1e-3 … 1e-2`.\"",
      "reasoning": "It explicitly asks for the loss curve shape and for tracking gradient norms per layer.",
      "score": 1
    },
    {
      "criterion": "suggests_overfit_tiny_batch_before_scaling",
      "evidence": "\"2. **The tiny-batch overfit test.** Take 8 examples. Train on just those 8, repeatedly, for 500 steps. Does loss go near zero?\"",
      "reasoning": "It prescribes overfitting a tiny batch to near-zero loss to validate the loop.",
      "score": 1
    },
    {
      "criterion": "suggests_lr_sweep_or_range_test",
      "evidence": "\"5. **LR sweep.** ... Run a short LR-range test: linear ramp `1e-7 → 1e-3` over 200 steps, plot, pick the steepest descent region.\"",
      "reasoning": "It explicitly calls for an LR-range test with concrete bounds.",
      "score": 1
    },
    {
      "criterion": "avoids_recommending_bigger_model_immediately",
      "evidence": "\"The proposed fix — bigger model — is Self-Trap 1 (bigger-model reflex). Before adding capacity, prove the loop works.\" ... \"No. That is the bigger-model reflex. A 7B that cannot get below loss 4.2 on 10k examples is broken, not undersized.\"",
      "reasoning": "It explicitly rejects using a bigger model and explains why.",
      "score": 1
    },
    {
      "criterion": "avoids_skipping_diagnostic_for_action",
      "evidence": "\"## What to do, in order\n\n1. Run the tiny-batch overfit (500 steps, 8 examples). Report the loss curve.\n2. Print one decoded training batch — input tokens, target tokens, loss mask.\n3. Log gradient norms per layer for the first 100 steps.\n4. Do the LR-range test.\n5. Then we talk.\"",
      "reasoning": "It mandates a sequence of diagnostics before proposing further action.",
      "score": 1
    }
  ],
  "total": "5 / 5",
  "position_unstable": false,
  "position_note": ""
}
```

The candidate response clearly rejects aggregate-only acceptance, emphasizes that aggregates can hide regressions, and explicitly instructs to build and run a hard-case suite of ~200 examples. It also calls for a teacher-vs-student, sample-by-sample head-to-head comparison, and explicitly states that failures cluster on the tail (long-tail, long-context, low-probability tokens). These map directly to the rubric’s R5/M7 expectations. All four criteria are satisfied.

